recordings.file-name: XC729935-crystallised song from a Garden Warbler Lough Ree 29th May 2022_HH_2.mp3
recordings.rmk: Prolonged crystallised song from a territorial Garden Warbler, presumably a male, in suitable breeding habitat. High pass filter applied below 300Hz, otherwise unaltered.
Male in display on breeding territory

I watched this Garden Warbler as it sang fairly continuously over the course of an hour.  It was in damp, mixed woods of alder, birch, elder, sycamore and oak. Blackcaps frequented the same habitat. At times, in the same part of the mixed woodland, the broadcast songs came from Blackcaps, not this Garden Warbler.  Some of the distinguishing characteristics that separate the vocals of the two species are evident on the recording. Such as? Well, Garden Warbler song is always faster than Blackcap. Being in a position to make a real world comparison between the speed of delivery between the two is difficult, of course. But once heard, the fast pace of Garden Warbler creates a kind of 'garbled' quality that is not shared by Blackcap, whose fast notes still seem well enunciated. Long continuous bursts are much more normal in Garden Warbler. Although Blackcap may also sing continuously, mainly at the start of the breeding season, Garden Warbler is the true 'endless rambler'. Even when there are breaks in Garden Warbler song, they are very brief, only about a second; Blackcap has longer pauses between song-bursts. Often Garden Warbler 'loses itself' in long, low passages that are also less loud than other passages that contain slightly more melodic (and Blackcap-like) song. On the clip there are 'long, low' passages at 1:10 for the next 30 seconds but you can hear the occasional slightly louder, more melodic interludes at 1:07 (for two seconds) and 1:16 (again, lasting about two seconds). The same pattern - long rambling but occasional rises in volume and 'better quality' notes - continues over the second minute of the clip with rises at 1:53, 2:02 and 2:30. Interestingly, the Garden Warbler seems to spot a Blackcap nearby at around 0:46 because it utters its 'chet ... chet' alarm call and - a nice comparison - the Blackcap sings once at 0:49. More Garden Warbler alarms follow the Blackcap's departure from 0:53 for the next ten seconds, for example at 0:55.

recordings.rmk: Song from a Garden Warbler, followed by a handful of calls as it moved off [five calls, one doubled, after 0:23]. Long song bursts are typical of Garden Warbler. The burst from 0:05 to 0:19 is not particularly long by Garden Warbler standards - but it would be longer than normal for a Blackcap. But there's a caveat: especially in early spring when male Blackcaps are setting up territories and the courtship season is in its first intense flush, males will indulge in song wars and individual songsters can sing continuously - for two minutes or more.

recordings.rmk:
337 verses of glorious Garden Warbler song. The bird is perched in a Hawthorn tree in an area of scattered scrub on a breezy morning. Note how the nearby Willow Warbler sings between the verses of the Garden Warbler rather than singing over the top of it. 

There are not many obvious examples of mimicry in this bird's song but it does appear to imitate a Dunnock at 30:07 and a Whitethroat at 24:51. 

Recorded with an Olympus LS-12 and Sennheiser ME66 handheld. EQ adjusted slightly below 1600 Hz to control the wind sounds and edited below 400 Hz to remove a few handling bumps and the deeper wind noise.

typical song
In a group of shrubs and trees in former bogland. Two males rivalling.

In most initial phases of afforestation on fertile riverside forest on open muddy partially sandy fertile alluvial soils matched with species “habitat pattern”=>: sparse long leafed shrubs of willows (here Salix purpurea L. – purple willow and young Salix alba L. – White Willow, Salix viminalis L. – common osier), overgrown by sparse young poplar tress (here Grey poplar (Populus × canescens) and young pure White Poplar (Populus alba)). This “habitat pattern” is proper also in any human origin similar afforestation, young woodlots or quite rarely gardens on fertile soils with signs of any similarity to flooding areas with open soils and matched shrubs and tree species- which I so to this date

Described “habitat pattern” is in contrast to similary singing Blackcap (Sylvia atricapilla) described here: XC103860 and Barred Warbler (Sylvia nisoria) described here: XC102157

This was very curious song! We don´t know exactly, could it be the Nightingale´s. The voice was utmost loud. - On the place there were so dense vegetation in trees that we saw the bird only partly and high in the tree. The plumage of bird was like the Nightingale´s, no stripe on breat and lower side. It has beige throat and breast. - However we seemed it has to be the uncommon way singing Nightingale.

Help us! Who knows? Comments, please.
Hannu Kivivuori
